A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
This budget line funds the SMPES PE. Legacy PEs 0101324F ISPAN and 0301112F NPES and NLCC DSS have been consolidated into one SMPES PE 0304100F.
The SMPES PE is comprised of two Budget Program Activity Codes (BPAC): SMPES and NLCC DSS.

 SMPES is an integrated enterprise solution software system providing the Department of War (DoW) and U.S. strategic nuclear forces' principal nuclear planning and
 analysis tools; including tools for consequence analysis and deliberate, adaptive, and crisis action planning for strategic deterrence.

 SMPES continues to consolidate the following six independently managed programs into one system: 1) Mission Planning and Analysis System (MPAS); 2)
 Global Adaptive Planning Collaborative Information Environment (GAP-CIE); 3) NLCC DSS - Nuclear Command and Control (NC2) Conference Module; 4) NPES
 Recapitalization (NPES Recap); 5) Force Status Readiness (FSR); and 6) Force Survivability Analysis and Management (FSAM).

 SMPES provides comprehensive global strike, coordinated space and missile defense, and information operations capabilities to meet strategic deterrent and national
 security objectives. SMPES consists of multiple sub-applications, working together to provide senior leaders with a strategic planning capability to U.S. Strategic
 Command (USSTRATCOM) leadership and war planners. SMPES software is utilized to develop Joint Staff Level I - IV nuclear and conventional attack options
 for national and theater requirements, by conducting continuous agile software development for classified and unclassified networks. SMPES supports the Unified
 Command Plan and Nuclear Posture Review (formerly known as MPAS).

 Special Access Program (SAP) Mission Planning and Distribution System (SMPDS) project: Supports baseline planning requirement of SMPES. This project supports a
 critical system of systems being designed to provide USSTRATCOM with the capability to integrate, plan, and distribute missions for emerging weapons systems. This
 system is essential for enhancing strategic deterrence and ensuring the effective planning of new military technologies.



